snippet.textDisplay:
Hi! I have been wondering about the scientific aspect of what affects the strength of a COVID-19 course of disease.
Obviously, it is not possible to argue beforehand whether someone's infection will cause them to go to the hospital or not. Patients in different countries are asked to remain at home when infected unless they're high risk (?) and to notify the doctors if the respiratory issues get really bad, so they can be moved to intense care. Also understandable, due to limited resources.
But I'm wondering WHY it can't be predicted. Even patients that are not classified as high-risk sometimes end up in intensive care, albeit with better survivability rates.

There are people out there carrying the virus without symptoms. There are some where it manifests like a flu. Some that have more serious symptoms but can still stay at home and get well. Some go to intensive care. I am wondering if the strength of symptoms is related to genetics in a more significant manner than, say, cases that have diabetes.

Do you know if any research in that area is being conducted, or at least data collected on the genetics of those tested positively and their symptoms, such that retroactively it can be worked out why some people don't show any symptoms at all, while others literally die of that virus?
Do you have any thoughts or theories on that, personally?

snippet.textDisplay:
Dear Doctor Mike,
It is so great of you to remind us at this time to focus on remaining calm and to be alert, not anxious. Would you please explain these numbers that are being reported of patients that have 'recovered' from COVID-19? I understand that the focus of our efforts around the world is primarily to avoid spreading this virus and keeping the number of cases as low as possible in order to protect those at the greatest risk and to keep hospitals from being inundated. But as an average citizen, who knows nothing about medicine, I don't understand what 'recovery' means in terms of this virus. Would this person be fully and completely healed, but remain a carrier and be at risk of infecting other people? Or is this just the number of people that were suspected to have the virus, but have been cleared?
Thank you.
